{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Finding\n\n`PlanContext` assembly (`orchestrator._assemble_context_uncached`) swallows child-enumeration and per-child-fetch failures with a bare `except Exception`, silently continuing with an empty/partial `children` list. Because `PlanContext.has_children` is `bool(self.children)`, a total enumeration failure also flips `has_children` to `False`, which makes container-scoped DET checks (confirmed: `det_floor.p5_task_dag`) return a trivial `pass` instead of reporting incompleteness — so a container whose hierarchy failed to load can still reach an unqualified clean PASS. This violates parent epic `6eca-183e-1cd2-4fb9` AC #4: \"Plan review cannot produce an ordinary clean pass when the ticket hierarchy was loaded incompletely, unless the omitted context is demonstrably irrelevant.\"\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/orchestrator.py:173-187` (`_assemble_context_uncached`): `list_tickets(parent=canonical, ...)` wrapped in `try/except Exception` -> `listed = []` on total failure (line 173-178); per-child `show_ticket` wrapped similarly (line 184-187), falling back to the list summary row on partial failure. Neither path records that anything was lost.\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/det_floor.py:104-138` (`PlanContext.has_children` property, line 133-138): `return bool(self.children)`. `p5_task_dag` (line 362-368): `if not ctx.has_children: return DetResult(\"P5\", \"task-dag\", \"pass\", coverage={\"ran\": True, \"children\": 0})` — confirms a wiped `children` list produces a silent P5 pass, not an incompleteness signal. `p8_reviewability`'s container pairing check (~line 598-604) is likewise skipped when `has_children` is `False`.\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/workflow_ops.py`: `plan_review_precheck` (def at line 135) calls `orchestrator.assemble_context` at line 140, giving it the REAL `pctx` in scope; its only `finalize_verdict` call is at line 209, **inside `plan_review_precheck`** (not `plan_review_coach`), with `coverage={\"det\": det_cov, \"llm_ran\": False}` (line 213). `plan_review_coach` (def at line 503) builds a **new, minimal** `PlanContext(ticket_id=..., ticket_type=..., title=\"\", description=\"\")` at line 540-545 (no `children`/hierarchy data) and calls `finalize_verdict` at line 557, with `coverage` built at line 546-550 from `ctx.inputs.get(\"det_coverage\")` (line 547) — i.e. call site 2 has no live `pctx` and must source everything from the precheck step's dict output.\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/orchestrator.py:503-541` (`finalize_verdict`): computes `verdict` from `coverage.get(...)` flags only (`llm_unavailable` line ~527, `verify_failed` line ~529); it does **not** read any attribute off its `ctx: PlanContext` argument today — confirming `coverage` (not the `ctx` object) is the correct, established plumbing point for a new flag.\n- `src/rebar/llm/workflow/gate_dispatch.py` has **three additional** `finalize_verdict` call sites beyond workflow_ops.py's two, none in the original plan:\n  - `_recover_plan_review_coach_failure` (def line 298), `coverage` built lines 324-329 from `precheck.get(\"det_coverage\")` (line 325) where `precheck = succeeded.get(STEP_PRECHECK)` (a **dict**, the recorded step output) — same shape as `plan_review_precheck`'s return value.\n  - `_recover_plan_review_verify_failure` (def line 342), `coverage` built lines 381-389, identical `precheck.get(\"det_coverage\")` pattern (line 382).\n  - `_degraded_plan_review_verdict` (def line 402), `coverage` built lines 420-426 from `det_floor.det_coverage(det_results)` (line 421) where `det_results = det_floor.run_det_floor(ctx)` (line 412) and `ctx` here **is** the caller's real `PlanContext` (passed straight through from `produce_plan_review_verdict`'s own `ctx` param, lines 145-147/185-187) — so this site, unlike the other two, has direct access to the real `pctx.hierarchy_incomplete` and doesn't need dict-threading.\n- `src/rebar/schemas/plan_review_precheck_output.schema.json`: `\"additionalProperties\": false` (line 17) and `\"required\": [...]` (line 16) list exactly `run_llm, verdict, canonical_id, ticket_type, det_blocking, det_advisory, det_coverage` — no room for new fields as written. `det_coverage` itself is declared as `{\"type\": \"object\", \"additionalProperties\": true}` (line 14) and IS in `required`.\n- `src/rebar/llm/workflow/lint_refs.py:445-450`: `props = schema.get(\"properties\")`, `literals = frozenset(props.keys())` — an output-contract ref-checker built directly from this schema's `properties`; an unlisted field name used in a `${{ steps.<id>.outputs.<name> }}` ref would lint as UNKNOWN.\n- Retry precedent: `_call_with_retry` genuinely exists, but at `src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/dispatch_one.py:113-139` (the **Jira reconciler**, not a generic helper), retrying on `JiraAPIError`/`urllib.error.HTTPError` (429/5xx only, 4xx fails fast) and `TimeoutError`, with `delays=[1,2,4]` seconds — an HTTP-transport-specific predicate that doesn't transfer to a local ticket-store read. `structured.py:294-297` / `runner.py:510-582` implement `OUTPUT_RETRIES=2`, a single bounded reask that feeds the model its own validation error back — also not applicable (LLM-output-validation-specific, not a plain read retry). `_reads.show_ticket`/`list_tickets` (`src/rebar/_reads.py:53-94`) raise a single broad `RebarError` on any failure (no typed transient/permanent split), matching `_assemble_context_uncached`'s existing bare `except Exception`. No reusable predicate/backoff precedent applies to this call; a bespoke tiny retry is justified, specified concretely below.\n\n## Remediation\n\n1. In `_assemble_context_uncached` (`orchestrator.py:163-211`), wrap the `list_tickets` call (line 174) in a bounded retry: **2 attempts total** (1 retry), catching the same broad `Exception` it catches today, with a **fixed 50ms delay** between attempts. On exhaustion set `pctx.hierarchy_incomplete = True` and `pctx.hierarchy_incomplete_detail = [\"enumeration\"]`. Add both fields to `PlanContext` (`det_floor.py:104-131`) with defaults `False` / `[]`. Apply the same bounded-retry-then-flag treatment to the per-child `show_ticket` fetch (line 184-187); on a per-child failure, append that child's id (not `\"enumeration\"`) to `hierarchy_incomplete_detail` and set `hierarchy_incomplete = True`, continuing with the summary row for that child (existing fallback behavior unchanged).\n2. Thread `hierarchy_incomplete`/`hierarchy_incomplete_detail` through **all five** `finalize_verdict` call sites via the `coverage` dict (the mechanism `finalize_verdict` already uses for `llm_unavailable`/`verify_failed`), sourced differently per site since only some have the real `pctx`:\n   - `workflow_ops.py:135` `plan_review_precheck`, call site line 209: real `pctx` in scope -> `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete\"] = pctx.hierarchy_incomplete`, `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\"] = pctx.hierarchy_incomplete_detail`. Also add both fields to the `base` dict (line 141-147) returned by this step so they flow to `ctx.inputs` downstream.\n   - `workflow_ops.py:503` `plan_review_coach`, call site line 557: no real `pctx` -> `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete\"] = ctx.inputs.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete\", False)`, `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\"] = ctx.inputs.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\", [])`, mirroring the existing `ctx.inputs.get(\"det_coverage\")` at line 547.\n   - `gate_dispatch.py:298` `_recover_plan_review_coach_failure`, coverage built ~line 324: `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete\"] = precheck.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete\", False)`, `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\"] = precheck.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\", [])` (same `precheck` dict already used for `det_coverage`).\n   - `gate_dispatch.py:342` `_recover_plan_review_verify_failure`, coverage built ~line 381: identical `precheck.get(...)` pattern.\n   - `gate_dispatch.py:402` `_degraded_plan_review_verdict`, coverage built ~line 420: real `ctx` (`PlanContext`) is passed straight through -> `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete\"] = getattr(ctx, \"hierarchy_incomplete\", False)`, `coverage[\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\"] = getattr(ctx, \"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\", [])`.\n3. In `finalize_verdict` (`orchestrator.py:503-541`), add `elif coverage.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete\"): verdict = \"INDETERMINATE\"` alongside the existing `llm_unavailable`/`verify_failed` branches (same `elif` chain, checked before falling through to PASS). No relevance-exception carve-out — see item 6 below for why.\n4. In `drift_floor._recompute_verdict_after_drop` (`drift_floor.py:190-211`), add the identical `elif cov.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete\"): verdict[\"verdict\"] = \"INDETERMINATE\"` branch so a dropped BLOCK re-derives INDETERMINATE, not PASS, at all three call sites: `drift_floor.apply_to_verdict` (call at `drift_floor.py:272`), `xcheck.apply_contradiction_drops` (def `xcheck.py:126`, call at `xcheck.py:180`), `xcheck.apply_comment_trail_drops` (def `xcheck.py:258`, call at `xcheck.py:311`).\n5. Update `src/rebar/schemas/plan_review_precheck_output.schema.json`: add to `properties` — `\"hierarchy_incomplete\": {\"type\": \"boolean\", \"description\": \"True iff child enumeration or a per-child fetch failed during context assembly.\"}` and `\"hierarchy_incomplete_detail\": {\"type\": \"array\", \"items\": {\"type\": \"string\"}, \"description\": \"Failed child ids, or [\\\"enumeration\\\"] on total list_tickets failure.\"}`. Do **not** add either to `required` — a missing key reads as falsy/empty everywhere it's consumed (item 2's `.get(..., False)`/`.get(..., [])`), so existing recorded verdicts / older step outputs without the field stay schema-valid. Leave `additionalProperties: false` as-is (both new keys are now declared).\n6. Parent-epic AC #4 reconciliation: parent epic `6eca-183e-1cd2-4fb9` AC #4 reads verbatim: *\"Plan review cannot produce an ordinary clean pass when the ticket hierarchy was loaded incompletely, unless the omitted context is demonstrably irrelevant.\"* This leaf intentionally implements the fail-closed half only, with no relevance-exception carve-out, because the exception's own trigger condition — \"the criteria that needed the missing context were still decided\" — cannot be stated safely here: confirmed via `det_floor.py:104-138`/`362-368` that a failed enumeration collapses `children` to `[]`, which flips `PlanContext.has_children` to `False`, which in turn makes exactly the container-scoped checks that would consume the missing hierarchy (`P5` confirmed; `P8`'s container pairing check similarly gated) return a trivial `pass` rather than running against absent data. So \"every criterion was decided despite incomplete context\" is never a real state to detect — the container-specific criteria are unconditionally the ones suppressed, meaning any relevance carve-out would be vacuous by construction. Always-INDETERMINATE is therefore the correct, narrower implementation of AC #4 for this context-assembly failure mode, not a deviation from it.\n7. Test-case content assertions: add a total-enumeration-failure test asserting `hierarchy_incomplete_detail == [\"enumeration\"]` exactly (not just that `hierarchy_incomplete` is truthy), and a partial-failure test (one child's `show_ticket` raises) asserting `hierarchy_incomplete_detail` contains that specific child's ticket id.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `PlanContext` gains `hierarchy_incomplete: bool = False` and `hierarchy_incomplete_detail: list[str] = []` (`det_floor.py`).\n- [ ] `_assemble_context_uncached`'s `list_tickets` call retries once (2 attempts total, 50ms fixed delay, same broad `Exception` predicate as today) before setting `hierarchy_incomplete=True`, `hierarchy_incomplete_detail=[\"enumeration\"]` on total failure.\n- [ ] The per-child `show_ticket` fetch gets the same bounded-retry-then-flag treatment; on a per-child failure the child's id is appended to `hierarchy_incomplete_detail` and `hierarchy_incomplete=True` is set, with the existing summary-row fallback unchanged.\n- [ ] `plan_review_precheck` (`workflow_ops.py:135`) reads `pctx.hierarchy_incomplete`/`pctx.hierarchy_incomplete_detail` directly (real `pctx` in scope) and threads both into its `base`/`coverage` dicts, used at its own `finalize_verdict` call (line 209).\n- [ ] `plan_review_coach` (`workflow_ops.py:503`) reads both fields via `ctx.inputs.get(...)` (mirroring `det_coverage`), NOT via any `pctx` attribute (its `pctx` at line 540 is a minimal reconstruction with no hierarchy data) — no contradiction between AC language and code here.\n- [ ] All three `gate_dispatch.py` recovery/degrade paths (`_recover_plan_review_coach_failure`, `_recover_plan_review_verify_failure`, `_degraded_plan_review_verdict`) thread `hierarchy_incomplete`/`hierarchy_incomplete_detail` into the `coverage` dict they build, per Remediation item 2 — five `finalize_verdict` call sites total are covered, not two.\n- [ ] `finalize_verdict` (`orchestrator.py`) and `drift_floor._recompute_verdict_after_drop` (`drift_floor.py:190-211`) each gain an `elif coverage.get(\"hierarchy_incomplete\"): verdict = \"INDETERMINATE\"` branch; the drift_floor branch is exercised through all three call sites (`drift_floor.apply_to_verdict`, `xcheck.apply_contradiction_drops`, `xcheck.apply_comment_trail_drops`).\n- [ ] `plan_review_precheck_output.schema.json` declares `hierarchy_incomplete` (boolean) and `hierarchy_incomplete_detail` (string array) in `properties`, neither in `required`; `additionalProperties: false` is preserved.\n- [ ] No relevance-exception carve-out is implemented; the ticket body documents why (Remediation item 6), citing parent epic `6eca-183e-1cd2-4fb9` AC #4 verbatim and the `has_children`/container-criteria-suppression mechanism that makes the carve-out's trigger condition unstatable.\n- [ ] Test coverage includes: (a) total-enumeration-failure -> `hierarchy_incomplete_detail == [\"enumeration\"]` exactly; (b) partial per-child failure -> `hierarchy_incomplete_detail` contains the specific failed child id; (c) both cases -> verdict is `INDETERMINATE` at at least one of the five `finalize_verdict` sites and survives a drift-floor/xcheck drop without reverting to PASS."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784734162499631001,"uuid":"388bccca-2b6a-48ec-b478-c9897182de2b"}